<subSubSection id="48D355CA8EEBFF6648A75042FE0CFE04" lastPageId="166" lastPageNumber="167" pageId="165" pageNumber="166" type="description">
<paragraph id="007606418EEBFF6648A75042FB76FE3F" blockId="165.[151,1437,1902,2035]" lastBlockId="166.[151,1437,151,968]" lastPageId="166" lastPageNumber="167" pageId="165" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538EEBFF6548A75042FE2DF877" bold="true" box="[151,392,1902,1927]" pageId="165" pageNumber="166">Description of male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="98F21AC48EEBFF6549AD5042FDABF876" box="[413,526,1902,1926]" captionStart="PLATE 43" captionStartId="164.[151,233,1962,1985]" captionTargetBox="[189,1356,216,1928]" captionTargetId="figure-60@164.[151,1436,193,1941]" captionTargetPageId="164" captionText="PLATE 43. A, B. Anteon sarawaki. A. Chela of holotype (from Olmi 1984). B. Male genitalia of paratype (from Olmi 1984). C. A. semipolitum, holotype. Length 2.62 mm. Scale bar 0.22 mm for A and 0.26 mm for B" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6412878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6412878/files/figure.png" pageId="165" pageNumber="166">Plate 43C</figureCitation>
). Fully winged; length 1.7–3.0 mm. Head black, except mandible testaceous; antenna testaceous; mesosoma black; metasoma brown; legs yellow-testaceous. Antenna filiform; antennal segments in following proportions: 12:6:8:8:6:7:7:6.5:6.5:8. Head dull; face strongly punctate, unsculptured among punctures; vertex and temples reticulate rugose; frontal line incomplete, only shortly present in front of anterior ocellus; POL = 7; OL = 4; OOL = 6; OPL = 4; TL = 4; greatest breadth of posterior ocelli shorter than OPL (3:4); occipital carina complete. In male 
<typeStatus id="DF72B8E38EE8FF6649B05790FE45FF24" box="[384,480,188,212]" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">paratype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingCountry id="78DE46D18EE8FF664A065790FD3EFF24" box="[566,667,188,212]" name="Thailand" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="65FD60868EE8FF664A9F5790FC9EFF24" box="[687,827,188,212]" degrees="16" direction="north" minutes="39.550" orientation="latitude" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" precision="1" value="16.659166">16°39.550'N</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="65FD60868EE8FF664B7B5790FC41FF24" box="[843,996,188,212]" degrees="101" direction="east" minutes="08.123" orientation="longitude" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" precision="1" value="101.13538">101°08.123'E</geoCoordinate>
, head, including vertex and temple, completely punctate and unsculptured among punctures. Pronotum short and rugose. Scutum, scutellum and metanotum shiny, smooth, finely punctate, unsculptured among punctures. Notauli incomplete, reaching approximately 0.6–0.7 length of scutum. Propodeum reticulate rugose, with strong transverse keel between dorsal and posterior surface; posterior surface with two complete longitudinal keels, median area smooth, unsculptured, and lateral areas rugose; rarely median area as rugose as lateral areas. Fore wing hyaline, without dark transverse bands; distal part of stigmal vein much shorter than proximal part (3:10). Paramere (
<figureCitation id="98F21AC48EE8FF664C7856B8FB17FE5C" box="[1096,1202,404,428]" captionStart="PLATE 42" captionStartId="163.[151,233,1845,1868]" captionTargetBox="[177,1409,238,1780]" captionTargetId="figure-110@163.[166,1421,217,1801]" captionTargetPageId="163" captionText="PLATE 42. A, C. Chelae, holotypes. B, D, E–G. Male genitalia. A. Anteon reticulatum (from Olmi 1984). B. A. reticulatum from Italy (from Olmi 1991). C. A. rugosum (from Xu &amp; He, 1997d). D. A. sabahnum from Brunei. E. A. sabahnum, holotype (from Olmi 1998a). F. A. semipolitum, holotype (from Olmi 2008c). G.A. silvestre, holotype (from Olmi 1984). Scale bar 0.34 mm for A, 0.25 mm for B, 0.16 mm for C and F, 0.18 mm for D, 0.23 mm for E and 0.12 mm for G." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5278514" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5278514/files/figure.png" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Plate 42F</figureCitation>
) without distal inner pointed process and with long and broad dorsal proximal membranous process. Tibial spurs 1/1/2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="007606418EE8FF6648F756F0FE0CFE04" blockId="166.[151,1437,151,968]" box="[199,425,476,500]" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538EE8FF6648F756F0FE80FE04" bold="true" box="[199,293,476,500]" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
